# clark-stealth-chromium patch 0010 — Notification permission consistency
#
# Source verified against:
#   chromium/main third_party/blink/renderer/modules/permissions/permission_status.cc
#   May 2026
#
# Idea source: Real Chrome reports `Notification.permission === "default"`
# until the user grants or denies. Headless mode auto-returns "denied"
# for many permissions, which bot detectors flag.
#
# Approach: SPEC — the actual default-denial happens in the browser-side
# PermissionContextBase / NotificationPermissionContext, not the renderer
# side. Need to confirm whether to patch at renderer-side
# PermissionStatus::Query or browser-side context. Verify with a
# stock-build run first.
#
# Test: launch headless, evaluate
#   navigator.permissions.query({name:'notifications'}).then(p => p.state)
# Expected: "prompt" or "granted" (NOT "denied").
#
# Depends on: 000-shared (probably), more discovery needed.
--- SPEC ---
File: chrome/browser/notifications/notification_permission_context.cc
      and/or  content/browser/permissions/permission_controller_impl.cc

The fix is upstream policy: when launched in headless mode AND no policy
has explicitly set notification permission, default to PROMPT not
DENIED. We don't introduce a new flag — we just stop the auto-deny that
headless does today.
